<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Chhattisgarh</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Heart of <em>India's Wilderness</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Chhattisgarh — carved out of Madhya Pradesh on November 1, 2000 — is one of India's last great frontiers: a vast, forested land where ancient tribal civilizations have lived in harmony with nature for thousands of years. Covering 135,192 sq km, nearly 44% of the state is blanketed in dense forest — one of the highest forest covers of any Indian state — home to tigers, leopards, barasingha, wild elephants and thousands of plant species found nowhere else. The state's name derives from the 36 (chhattis) forts (garh) of the Haihaya Rajput kingdom that once ruled these lands. Chhattisgarh is the tribal heartland of India: over 32% of its population belongs to scheduled tribes — Gond, Baiga, Halba, Kamar, Muria, Maria and dozens more — each with their own language, art, music, deity and way of being. The Bastar region in the south is perhaps the most extraordinary tribal landscape remaining in Asia: dense sal forests, thundering waterfalls, ancient cave paintings, and village weekly markets (haats) where tribal communities trade in age-old rhythms. The state sits atop enormous mineral wealth — iron ore, coal, bauxite, limestone — yet its true wealth lies in its waterfalls. Chitrakote — the Niagara of India — Tirathgarh, Amrit Dhara, Ramdaha and dozens more cascade through forested gorges. Chhattisgarh's temple heritage at Sirpur, Rajim and Ratanpur preserves some of India's finest early medieval sculpture. This is India still wild, still ancient, still breathing freely.</p>
</section>

